YES ✅ — exactly.

Whenever you see:

NoMethodError

It ultimately comes from Ruby’s default method_missing implementation.

Now let’s understand this very clearly.

🔍 What Actually Happens Internally

When you call:

obj.some_method

Ruby does this:

Search in object's class

Search in included modules

Search in superclass

Keep going up the ancestor chain

If still not found…

👉 Ruby calls:

method_missing(:some_method)
🧠 Where Does NoMethodError Come From?

Ruby has a built-in method_missing defined in BasicObject.

If you do NOT override it, that default version does:

raise NoMethodError

So yes:

NoMethodError is raised by Ruby’s default method_missing.

🧪 Example
class A
end

A.new.hello

Ruby internally does:

A.new.method_missing(:hello)

Since you didn’t define method_missing,
Ruby uses the default one → raises NoMethodError.

⚠️ Important Twist

If YOU override method_missing and don’t call super,
then NoMethodError may never happen.

Example:

class A
  def method_missing(name, *args)
    "I handled it"
  end
end

A.new.hello

Now:

✔ No error
✔ Because you intercepted it

But if you write:

class A
  def method_missing(name, *args)
    super
  end
end

Now Ruby goes to parent’s method_missing
and that raises NoMethodError.

🎯 Interview-Level Answer

If interviewer asks:

“Where does NoMethodError come from?”

Correct answer:

When Ruby cannot find a method in the method lookup chain, it invokes method_missing. If method_missing is not overridden, Ruby’s default implementation raises NoMethodError.

